<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-113-188 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 838 532</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Shopper  July 1991 v11 n7 p111(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dell and Microsoft go online: new support services allow forcustomer/vendor interaction. (Dell Computer Corp.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dell Computer Corp. (Services)Microsoft Corp. (Services).andO;Ticker:    DELL; MSFT.andO;Topic:     On-LineSupport ServicesCustomer Relations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Stuck on a technical problem?andP;  Now you can go straight to the source for ananswer--that is, if you're a customer of either Dell or Microsoft.andM;In what some industry executives believe will be a growing trend for the1990s, the two companies--separately--have set up online programs that theircustomers can use to contact designated technical-support staffers.andM;Dell Computer's program, which runs over CompuServe, enables customers toexchange ideas or obtain product information.andP;  Dell's telephone supporttechnicians regularly monitor Compuserve on a rotational basis.andP;  Users canalso access a library that contains technical information on Dell products,as well as communicate in an electronic forum with other Dell users.andM;&quot;For our channel, this is the best source of information--getting it straightfrom the manufacturer,&quot; said Dell's vp for service and support, Roy Sovine.andM;In a similar fashion, Microsoft's Support Advantage program allows its usersto directly quiz Microsoft support engineers.andP;  Customers can also access anonline databse of technical product information, scan bulletin boards, sendE-mail, and check Microsoft's &quot;What's New&quot; listing.andM;The subscription price for Microsoft's Support Advantage program ranges from$295 to $795 per year.andP;  The regular CompuServe connect-time rates apply forthose people who use the Dell service.andO;</TEXT></DOC>